I was kinda bothered by how the services section looks like on smaller devices, being that you have the content, then 2 pictures/illustrations one after another, then another content, which seemed off. 
So after some googling I've come up with this solution:

1. In the web development content, change the class of a row to row--1, should be directly after the START WEB DEVELOPMENT CONTENT comment.
2. Nest this code in services like this:

 .services {

   .row--1 {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: row;



    @include media-breakpoint-down(sm) {        
        flex-direction: column-reverse;
        
        }
    }
}

I don't know if this is the best approach but it works and looks much better in my opinion.

The gradient did not work for me in the navbar - at around 46:12, but I managed to solve it using @use AND @forward. 

Here is how:


Based on another video "Stop using @import with Sass" I:
1) Created 2 extra files in Components and Sections called "_index.scss"



2) In Components it contains:
@forward "animations";
@forward "buttons";
@forward "mixins";
@forward "typography";
and in Sections:
@forward "navbar";
@forward "intro-section";
@forward "companies";
@forward "services";
@forward "testimonials";
@forward "faq";
@forward "portfolio";
@forward "get-started";
@forward "footer";


3) Then in style.scss I only have:
@use "custom";

@use "Components"; //importing components 
@use "Sections"; //import sections
(instead of the things in  (0:35:39) Part 3: File structure )


That's it! Now the gradients finally works for me :)

